":"1455","1388":"1388","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","1386":"1386","before 1392":"before 1392","1419":"1419","1427":"1427","Farnsworth, Lancs., Eng.":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Farnworth, Lancaster, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Farneworth, Lancs., England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hulton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Hulton (Lancashire) or Hulton (Staffordshire), both from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Hilton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hilton","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","habitational name from any of various places called Hilton (e.g. in Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Staffordshire, North Yorkshire, and Westmorland), most of which derive from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some come from Old English <i>helde</i> ‘slope’ + <i>tūn</i>.","occasionally, as in the case of Ralph <i>filius Hilton</i> (Yorkshire 1219), perhaps from the personal name <i>Hilton</i>, itself a possible form of Norman <i>Hildun</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’. Compare   Hilt  . This English surname is present in Ireland (mainly taken to Ulster in the early 17th century, though recorded earlier in Dublin)."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":67,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When James de Hulton was born in 1388, in Farnworth, Lancashire, England, his father, John de Hulton, was 30 and his mother, Elizabeth Atherton, was 27. He married Elizabeth Molyneux in 1414. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1388–":"1388–Surnud","1386–Male":"1386–Surnud","1388–Female":"1388–Surnud","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1399–Female":"1399–Surnud","1397–1442":"1397–1442","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1421–Male":"1421–Surnud","1424–1460":"1424–1460","1427–Female":"1427–Surnud","1358–Male":"1358–Surnud","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","ABT 1419":"umbes 1419","abt.1427":"umbes 1427","1362":"1362","1460":"1460","abt 1421":"umbes 1421","1414":"1414","1424":"1424","1358":"1358","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1421":"1421","1399":"1399","1442":"1442","1397":"1397","1386":"1386","before 1392":"enne 1392","1419":"1419","1427":"1427","Farnsworth, Lancs., Eng.":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Farnworth, Lancaster, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Farneworth, Lancs., England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1388–":"1388–Kuollut","1386–Male":"1386–Kuollut","1388–Female":"1388–Kuollut","1388–Male":"1388–Kuollut","1399–Female":"1399–Kuollut","1397–1442":"1397–1442","1419–Male":"1419–Kuollut","1421–Male":"1421–Kuollut","1424–1460":"1424–1460","1427–Female":"1427–Kuollut","1358–Male":"1358–Kuollut","1362–Female":"1362–Kuo